      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To address the security scanner's concerns, I'd recommend refactoring the login function to use parameterized queries or prepared statements. Here's an updated version:\n\n```python\nimport sqlite3\n\ndef login_user(username, password):\n    conn = sqlite3.connect('users.db')\n    cursor = conn.cursor()\n    \n    query = \"SELECT * FROM users WHERE username = ? AND password = ?\"\n    cursor.execute(query, (username, password))\n    user = cursor.fetchone()\n    \n    conn.close()  # Close the connection to avoid resource leaks\n    \n    if user:\n        return True\n    else:\n        return False\n```\n\nBy using parameterized queries, you avoid directly injecting user input into the query string, which reduces the risk of SQL injection attacks. This should help pass the security scanner's checks.",
